%N A391165 Primitive cubic pyritohedral numbers: a(n) = 864*n^3 - 2484*n^2 + 2384*n - 763.
%C A391165 These are figurate numbers produced in the construction of approximate pyritohedrons (dodecahedrons with irregular pentagonal faces) using points in a primitive cubic lattice. The dihedral angle along the long edges for such a pyritohedron is 2*arctan(2) = A197376.
%C A391165 The n-th term is expressed as a summation which takes (8n-7)^3 and adds 6 stacks - each layer the number of points. The stacks increase by 2 layers with unit increment in n, totaling 2n-2 layers. This corresponds to constructing a pyritohedron by taking a cube and placing a wedge on each of its 6 faces.
%C A391165 So, a(n) = (8*n-7)^3 + 6*Sum_{i=2..n} (6*n+2*i-9)*(8*i-15) + (6*n+2*i-9)*(8*i-11).
%C A391165 Using cubes (with edge lengths same as the lattice spacing) centered at these figurate points to construct such polyhedra is known as Haűy construction.
